# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: envoy-proxy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:envoy-proxy/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:envoy-proxy/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:envoy-proxy/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:envoy-proxy/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:envoy-proxy/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:envoy-proxy/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:envoy-proxy/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:envoy-proxy/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:envoy-proxy/what-is-envoy] Envoy is an L7 proxy and communication bus designed for large modern service oriented architectures.
[src:envoy-proxy/what-is-envoy] In practice, achieving the previously stated goal is incredibly difficult.
